    <%# ── §7 Edge Cases ───────────────────────────────────────────────────── %>
    <div class="dp-section" id="edge-cases">
      <div class="dp-section-header">
        <div class="dp-section-num">§7</div>
        <h2>System Rules &amp; Edge Cases</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="dp-table-wrap"><table class="dp-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Scenario</th><th>Detection</th><th>System Response</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Event overload (high volume)</strong></td>
            <td>Table row count exceeds <code>kMaxTableRows</code> (default: 5 000).</td>
            <td>Oldest rows (bottom of table) are removed to maintain the cap. A WARN event is emitted: "Event buffer capped at 5000 rows — oldest events trimmed from view (database not affected)."</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Missing EventMetadata</strong></td>
            <td>API returns null for <code>metadata</code> key when a row is selected.</td>
            <td>Right pane shows "Metadata not available" placeholder. Event ID, Severity, Timestamp, and Service are still populated from the <code>SystemEvent</code> root record. No error dialog.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Corrupted payload</strong></td>
            <td>Payload JSON fails to parse (<code>JSON.parse</code> throws).</td>
            <td>Raw payload viewer shows: <code>{"error": "Payload could not be decoded", "raw": "{raw bytes truncated at 512 chars}"}</code>. A WARN event is emitted for the corruption.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Node offline</strong></td>
            <td>Health endpoint returns 5xx, or network timeout occurs in <code>refreshNodeHealth()</code>.</td>
            <td>Node card status changes to red dot "Offline". A CRITICAL event is emitted: "Health check failed for {node_name} — unreachable". Health timer continues polling every 30 s. When the node recovers, status updates automatically and an INFO event confirms: "{node_name} is back online."</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Delayed logs</strong></td>
            <td>Event timestamp is more than 5 minutes in the past relative to current time.</td>
            <td>The event is inserted normally into the stream (newest-first by actual timestamp). A "⚠ Delayed" label is appended to the timestamp cell in orange: <code>2026-04-17 09:10:00.000 ⚠ Delayed</code>. Delayed events do not affect live-tail scroll behavior.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Duplicate events</strong></td>
            <td><code>SystemEvent.event_id</code> already exists in the table.</td>
            <td>Duplicate is discarded before row insertion. The existing row is not updated. A WARN is emitted to the console (not to the table): "Duplicate event_id suppressed: {event_id}".</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Time sync issues</strong></td>
            <td>Event timestamp is in the future relative to the local clock by more than 60 seconds.</td>
            <td>A WARN event is emitted: "Clock skew detected — event timestamp {ts} is {N}s ahead of local clock. Verify NTP sync." The event is still inserted.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>RBAC violation attempt</strong></td>
            <td>A non-admin role attempts to access the System Events tab (e.g. from deep link or API).</td>
            <td>Tab is hidden from tab bar at startup. If the tab is somehow reached: <code>QMessageBox::warning</code> shown and tab index is reset to the previous tab. A SECURITY_ALERT AUDIT event is emitted: "Unauthorized access attempt to System Events tab by role: {role}".</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>logs.txt cannot be written</strong></td>
            <td>File open fails due to permissions or disk full.</td>
            <td>Events continue to be inserted into the in-memory table only. A CRITICAL event is emitted: "Persistent log write failed — {error}. Events are not being persisted to disk." The table remains fully functional.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table></div>
    </div>

    <%# ── §8 End-to-End User Flow ─────────────────────────────────────────── %>
    <div class="dp-section" id="user-flow">
      <div class="dp-section-header">
        <div class="dp-section-num">§8</div>
        <h2>End-to-End User Interaction Flow</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="dp-flow">
        <div class="dp-step">
          <h4>Tab Open — RBAC Check</h4>
          <p>
            The application calls <code>sysEventsApplyRbac()</code> on construction.
            <code>SCUIUtil::ReadFromSmartcheqConfig("wizard_operator_role")</code> is evaluated.
            If the role is not <code>system_admin</code>, <code>admin</code>, or
            <code>administrator</code>, the tab at index 6 is hidden via
            <code>tabWidgetTopLeft→setTabVisible(6, false)</code>. The Export, Clear Terminal,
            and Clear Cache buttons are also disabled. For a valid system_admin, the tab is
            visible and all controls are enabled.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="dp-step">
          <h4>Infrastructure Health Load</h4>
          <p>
            On tab show, <code>refreshNodeHealth()</code> fires immediately, issuing
            <code>GET {F5URL}/api/v2/health</code> with Bearer token. The response JSON is
            dispatched to <code>applyNodeHealthJson()</code>, which populates all six node cards
            with status dots, metric values, and last-sync timestamps.
            A QTimer is started at 30-second intervals for subsequent refreshes.
            An INFO event is emitted: "Infrastructure health loaded — 6 nodes polled."
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="dp-step">
          <h4>Event Stream Begins (Live Mode)</h4>
          <p>
            The Qt6 console begins routing all <code>qInfo()</code> / <code>qWarning()</code> /
            <code>qCritical()</code> messages through <code>setConsoleProcessing()</code>.
            Each message passes the noise filter, severity detector, action code detector
            (if AUDIT), and row inserter. Live-tail is on by default — the table scrolls to the
            top on each new row so the latest event is always visible.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="dp-step">
          <h4>User Applies Filters</h4>
          <p>
            The operator types a keyword into <code>sysEventsSearchBar</code> or selects
            a severity from <code>logLevelCombo</code>. <code>applySysEventFilter()</code>
            runs synchronously on the UI thread — no API call. Rows that do not match are
            hidden; AUDIT rows are exempted from the severity gate but still hide if the keyword
            does not match their message or event ID.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="dp-step">
          <h4>User Selects an Event Row</h4>
          <p>
            The operator clicks a row. <code>onSysEventRowSelected()</code> extracts the
            <code>event_id</code> from column 3 and issues
            <code>GET {F5URL}/api/v2/system_events/{event_id}</code>.
            The API returns the full <code>SystemEvent</code> + <code>EventMetadata</code>
            + (if error) <code>TraceStack</code> + <code>CryptographicReference</code> object.
            All five right-pane sub-panels are populated from this single response.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="dp-step">
          <h4>Forensic Inspection</h4>
          <p>
            The operator reviews the Event Metadata (ID, Severity, Timestamp, Node, Correlation),
            the raw Request Payload (sensitive fields redacted), and — if the event is an error —
            the Trace Stack showing the exact file:line of the error origin.
            For AUDIT events tied to a CBDC batch, the Cryptographic Reference panel shows the
            manifest hash and its verification status. The operator may copy the hash and
            switch to the Validation Desk tab to cross-reference the batch record.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="dp-step">
          <h4>Export Logs</h4>
          <p>
            The operator clicks <strong>Export Terminal Logs</strong>. A save dialog opens.
            On confirmation, all rows in the table (visible and hidden) are written to the
            chosen file as plain text. A <code>QMessageBox::information</code> confirms success.
            An AUDIT event is written: <code>[ACTION: BATCH_OPERATION] | Terminal logs exported</code>.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="dp-step">
          <h4>Audit Trail Written</h4>
          <p>
            Every action taken in the System Events tab that carries administrative intent is
            itself an AUDIT-tier system event. The tab monitors itself: clearing the terminal,
            clearing the cache, and exporting logs each produce their own AUDIT event with
            the operator's node ID and timestamp. These self-referential audit events are
            written to the persistent <code>logs.txt</code> file and to the PostgreSQL
            <code>system_events</code> table before the operation completes.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <%# ── §9 Architecture Notes ───────────────────────────────────────────── %>
    <div class="dp-section" id="architecture">
      <div class="dp-section-header">
        <div class="dp-section-num">§9</div>
        <h2>Architecture Notes</h2>
      </div>

      <h3>Event Ingestion Pipeline</h3>
      <p>
        Events originate from two sources: (1) the Qt6 application via the Qt message handler
        callback registered with <code>qInstallMessageHandler</code>, which routes all
        <code>qInfo/qWarning/qCritical/qDebug</code> calls through
        <code>setConsoleProcessing()</code>; and (2) the Rails backend via
        <code>Rails.logger</code> and Sidekiq job lifecycle hooks.
      </p>
      <div class="dp-rule">
        Qt6 message handler → setConsoleProcessing()<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;→ noise filter (discard UI telemetry)<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;→ sysEvt_detectSeverity()   (AUDIT checked first)<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;→ sysEvt_detectAuditAction() (if AUDIT)<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;→ appendSysEventRow()        (insert at row 0, apply filter, scroll if live)<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;→ persist to logs.txt        (append write, UTF-8)<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;→ POST /api/v2/system_events (async, background thread)<br>
        <br>
        Rails logger → SystemEvent.create()      (synchronous within request)<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;→ EventMetadata.create()     (async via Sidekiq job)<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;→ TraceStack.create()        (if exception, async)
      </div>

      <h3>Logging Service — Centralized Design</h3>
      <p>
        A single logging service class (<code>SystemEventLogger</code>) in
        <code>app/services/system_event_logger.rb</code> is the sole writer for all backend
        events. It accepts <code>severity</code>, <code>service_source</code>,
        <code>message</code>, <code>node_id</code>, and optional <code>payload</code>.
        It constructs the <code>event_id</code>, calls
        <code>SystemEvent.create!</code>, and enqueues
        <code>SystemEventMetadataJob</code> for async enrichment.
        Rails controllers call it via:
      </p>
      <div class="dp-rule">
        SystemEventLogger.log(severity: "AUDIT", service: "Rails",<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;message: "[ACTION: AUTHORITY_APPROVE] | #{proposal.proposal_id}",<br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;node_id: current_node_id, payload: request_payload)
      </div>

      <h3>Storage</h3>
      <div class="dp-table-wrap"><table class="dp-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Store</th><th>Contents</th><th>Retention</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>PostgreSQL (<code>system_events</code> table)</td><td>All <code>SystemEvent</code> records and their associated <code>EventMetadata</code>, <code>TraceStack</code>, <code>CryptographicReference</code></td><td>365 days default (configurable via <code>wizard_log_retention_days</code> in Security preferences)</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>logs.txt</code> (flat file)</td><td>Plain-text append log from the Qt6 client. Cleared by Clear Cache action. Human-readable without a database.</td><td>Until manually cleared or Clear Cache is invoked</td></tr>
          <tr><td>PostgreSQL (<code>governance_votes</code>, <code>validation_events</code>)</td><td>Cross-tab audit records referenced by <code>correlation_id</code></td><td>Permanent (immutable)</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table></div>

      <h3>Streaming Mechanism</h3>
      <p>
        Phase 1 (current): The Qt6 client uses a <strong>local message handler callback</strong>
        for events originating from its own process, and a <strong>30-second polling timer</strong>
        for infrastructure health. There is no WebSocket connection in Phase 1.
      </p>
      <p>
        Phase 2 (planned): The Rails API will expose an ActionCable WebSocket channel
        (<code>SystemEventsChannel</code>). The Qt6 client will subscribe via the
        <code>QtWebSockets</code> module and receive pushed events in real time,
        eliminating the polling gap for backend-originated events.
      </p>

      <h3>Integration with Governance Audit Logs</h3>
      <div class="dp-callout dp-info">
        <span class="dp-ci">ℹ</span>
        <div>
          The System Events tab shares the <strong>same audit trail infrastructure</strong>
          as the Governance tab. When a board vote is cast (<code>GovernanceVote</code>)
          or a policy is anchored (<code>DLTAnchor</code>), a corresponding
          <code>SystemEvent</code> with <code>severity: AUDIT</code> and the appropriate
          <code>action_code</code> is written by <code>SystemEventLogger</code>. The
          <code>correlation_id</code> ties the <code>SystemEvent</code> to the
          <code>GovernanceProposal.id</code>, enabling forensic investigators to trace
          the full chain: proposal creation → voting → quorum → DLT anchor, all within
          a single System Events query filtered by correlation ID.
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>API Reference</h3>
      <div class="dp-table-wrap"><table class="dp-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>Path</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>GET</td><td class="f">/api/v2/health</td><td>Infrastructure health envelope. Returns <code>{ rails: {}, dlt: {node_1: {}, node_2: {}}, hsm: {}, postgresql: {}, nginx: {} }</code>. Polled every 30 seconds by Qt6 client.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>GET</td><td class="f">/api/v2/system_events</td><td>List events. Params: <code>severity</code>, <code>service_source</code>, <code>node_id</code>, <code>correlation_id</code>, <code>from_ts</code>, <code>to_ts</code>, <code>limit</code> (default 200). Returns array of <code>SystemEvent</code> objects newest-first.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>GET</td><td class="f">/api/v2/system_events/:event_id</td><td>Full event detail. Returns <code>SystemEvent</code> + nested <code>metadata</code>, <code>trace_stack</code> (if error), <code>cryptographic_reference</code> (if AUDIT). Used by right-pane panel population.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>POST</td><td class="f">/api/v2/system_events</td><td>Write event from Qt6 client. Body: <code>{ severity, service_source, message, node_id, correlation_id, payload }</code>. Returns <code>{ event_id }</code>.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>GET</td><td class="f">/api/v2/system_events/export</td><td>Download all events as a plain-text log file. Params: <code>from_ts</code>, <code>to_ts</code>, <code>severity</code>. Returns <code>Content-Type: text/plain</code> file attachment.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table></div>

